description: Have I had bad experiences with employers? Hell yeah. I’ve had 3 professional jobs from 2001-2021 (one before law school & two as an attorney) & all 3 had massive toxic traits. But I don’t base this video on that experience. I base it on 14 years of experience as an employment attorney where I represented employees & studied countless cases. I’ve lost count of how many case holdings I’ve read. These records are all public & anyone can access them. You can google it. In addition to public records, I also saw all the confidential agreements & arbitrations of the cases I worked on which are not public & I cannot discuss. Many people think I was only speaking from personal experience when in fact, this is the nature of most workplaces in America. Are there exceptions? Of course there are. Regardless of whether you agree or disagree with my sentiments, I hope you take away the lesson that we should all be building an FU Fund. I first heard this term from JL Collins, the author of a Simple Path to Wealth. Why? Because financial independence is something we should all strive for to help build security & stability in good times & especially in bad times. If the last 2 years hasn’t taught us that I don’t know what will. I wouldn’t bank on an employer’s good graces as my safety net. That doesn’t mean you can’t be friendly at work. Of course you can & you should! But not every colleague deserves your trust & the details about your private life. Use your judgement & be really picky about who you confide in. DO NOT ever think that HR is your friend. They’re there to represent the company, PERIOD. Many HR managers agreed in the comments of this video so keep that in mind. FU Fund means saying FU to anything or anyone that steals your peace & all it takes is one new manager or coworker to ruin a perfectly fine work environment. Don’t ever get so comfortable you forget to CYA because I GUARANTEE you your boss & your company is doing just that.

description: There was a TikTok that went viral about a guy bragging that he works 105 hours a week on an oil rig and that anyone who works less than that better “check themselves.” Sir, you are the one that has been checked by capitalism. CheckMate.⁠ ⁠ People in the United States work more hours and take the least amount of vacation than any other country in the world. Work has become our personality trait. It’s why we ask people “what do you do?” as one of the first questions when we meet them. In other countries, that’s actually a very rude question.⁠ ⁠ In a way, we’ve all been brainwashed to believe this. That working is honorable. That working many, many hours is the right thing, even if you’re not getting paid for it. That excessive labor is sanctioned by religion even.⁠ ⁠ This is unique to our country. And although it has led to so much innovation and financial success, it is not without its cost. The wealth gap is wider than ever. We are in more debt than ever. We can’t even afford to do the things that our parents could afford to do, like buy a home. Because corporations are gobbling up real estate and jacking up the price.⁠ ⁠ All of this is to say: If you’re working 70+ hours a week, you are probably being exploited (assuming you’re not being paid multiple six-figures). Many people who leave these types of positions are often replaced by two or three workers because they knew how much work you were doing and they took advantage of you for as long as you let them.⁠ ⁠ I hope that you take some time to assess your situation and realize that your health is the priority and you should be working on an exit strategy. Working that many hours for a prolonged period of time is physically and mentally damaging. If you’re in a position to make a change, I hope that you can. Not everyone is able to, and for that, we have to keep demanding better labor practices from these corporations.⁠ ⁠ It’s time to create an exit strategy!

description: In an ideal world, everyone could do both. But the truth is that there’s no way to front your children’s college education, buy a home, invest for your retirement, and cover all of life’s emergencies. Investing will help some of that if you start early. You can start investing for your kid’s education now with a 529 plan or just a plain brokerage account. You can invest for a downpayment on a house if you’re 10+ years away from buying. It’s all about starting ASAP. But if you don’t have decades ahead of you, then you’ll likely have to make some hard choices. But the good news is that you can gift your kids the knowledge that you didn’t have 10-20 years ago. And they’ll be better for it even if it’s not you handing them over a check. Let’s focus on making sure you’re taken care of because taking care of your retirement is a gift to your children as well. It’s the peace of mind they’ll appreciate when they’re older.

description: There’s a line between investing for the future and hoarding out of fear. The skills you need to save, invest, and make money are not the same skills needed to spend your money. Many people forget this. Spending is a crucial step to living the life you dream of. But so many become fearful and can’t seem to let go of their frugal ways. That’s why it’s important to understand your numbers.  It’s important to know that if you spend X that you’re still on track to achieve Y. Without this clarity it’s very easy for fear to seep in and for hoarding to become a way of life.  And wouldn’t that be a shame?

description: Someone on Twitter said I was contributing to fake class warfare with this tweet. WUT?⁠ ⁠ I didn't start the fire, buddy. It was always burning. (Thank you, Billy Joel!)⁠ ⁠ You don't have to go very far to see that the wealthy just use money in a completely different way than we do. They don't even sell their investments to live off of it. They BORROW against it.⁠ ⁠ That's right. They go to the bank and show them their big, fat investment accounts and say, "Hey, Bank. Look at all this stock I have. I don't want to sell it though, because I don't want to get taxed. Can you lend me money instead, and I'll use my investment as collateral?" And the bank goes, "Sure!" And they all laugh, and laugh, and laugh.⁠ ⁠ And don't get me started on "margin," which basically means buying stocks using debt! Oh, it's not debt, it's margiiiiinnnn. Doesn't that sound so much sexier?⁠ ⁠ And when it all goes to shit, guess who declares bankruptcy, or gets bailed out by the government? Yup, those mega-rich guys. Not you and not me.⁠ ⁠ So get off people's backs about their student loans. The system was rigged the day we signed that paperwork. As someone who's paid $150,000 in student loans and someone who pays more taxes than the average American (multiple-six figures), I am TOTALLY FINE WITH LOAN FORGIVENESS!⁠

description: Have you heard of the 4% rule? I’ll cover this during class.  It allows you to withdraw from your portfolio (sell some of your stocks) while allowing the rest of your portfolio to continue growing and compounding. This way you never run out of money. This concept LITERALLY changed my life. I had no idea that this was possible and that it would pave the way for my early retirement goals. Even if you don’t want to retire early, you need to know how this works so you understand how much you need to have invested by the time you do decide to stop working. And remember that the 4% rule is a guideline and that we need to remain flexible.  Some years you may have to withdraw 2% or 3% but some other years you may get to withdraw 5% or 6% depending on how the market’s doing.

description: I started investing when I was 28 which I thought was early until I met these kids on TikTok who have been investing since they were 18 😅 Anyhoo, I’ve learned a few lessons during this time: ✅ There are no get rich quick schemes & a lot more ways to lose money. Investing works If you’re in it for the long term. Decades not weeks. This is why I don’t day trade. ✅ 401Ks & IRAs and all other retirement accounts are GREAT. They lower the tax burden today & tomorrow depending on which ones you choose & the funds offered in them have improved over time. ✅ There are LEGAL tax loopholes for accessing these accounts early. I’ll reshare my video about this in my stories. ✅ Investing is simple but it’s not intuitive — you need to learn how it works so you’re prepared for market downturns & staying on track with your investment plan.

description: Reposting this since it’s been a year since I moved to Portugal! $17k for 2 years of health insurance is INSANE and I knew that. But having reliable health insurance when I needed is SO WORTH it to me. PRO TIP: If you’re quitting a full time job to become self employed, do NOT take COBRA. You can’t deduct it as a business expense since it’s an employer-sponsored plan even though you’re paying in full. Just get your own policy directly from an insurance company or through the marketplace. I definitely could’ve gone with a cheaper insurance plan. An HMO would’ve cost half. But if I need a specialist I don’t want to be forced to go to an in-network doctor instead of the one I prefer. I don’t want to ask for a referral every time. And last but definitely NOT LEAST, I can easily afford this cost. Most people cannot. And just because I can afford it doesn’t make it any less absurd. I even had my gyno trying to tell me that I should cancel it and just pay her directly. Sounds nice while you’re healthy but not so great if you need life-saving surgery.
